# OS files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
desktop.ini

# Editor folders
.vscode/
.idea/
*.sublime-project
*.sublime-workspace

# Logs
*.log
npm-debug.log*

# Environment / secrets (never commit these)
.env
.env.local
*.key

# Node (if you ever add a build step later)
node_modules/
dist/
```

The most important lines here are `.env` and `*.key` — these prevent you from accidentally committing any API keys or secrets if you ever expand the project later.

---

## Which license to pick?

| License | Best for | Restriction |
|---|---|---|
| **MIT** | Most open, recommended | Must keep your copyright notice |
| **Apache 2.0** | Larger projects | Same as MIT + patent protection |
| **GPL v3** | If you want forks to stay open source | Forks must also be open source |
| **No license** | Private / all rights reserved | Nobody can legally use your code |

For a free public tool like Veritas, **MIT is the sweet spot** — simple, permissive, widely recognized.

---

## Your final repo structure should look like
```
veritas-checker/
├── index.html       ← your app
├── LICENSE          ← MIT license
├── .gitignore       ← ignore rules
└── README.md        ← auto-created by GitHub
